df = pd.read_csv("../data/heart.csv")

Questions to answer:¶

What are the reasons for heart disease¶

Who are the people most vulnerable to it¶

Data Schema¶

-age¶

-sex (1 = male; 0 = female)¶

-chest pain type (4 values)¶

-resting blood pressure¶

-serum cholesterol in mg/dl¶

-fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl¶

-resting electrocardiographic results (values 0,1,2)¶

-maximum heart rate achieved¶

-exercise induced angina¶

-oldpeak = ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest¶

-the slope of the peak exercise ST segment¶

-number of major vessels (0-3) colored by fluoroscopy¶

-thal: 1 = normal; 2 = fixed defect; 3 = reversable defec,¶

-target: presence of heart disease¶

Main problems with the data:¶

Small sample¶

Skewed data (we don't have enough samples for every gender at every age, same can be said for almost every feature column)¶

Majority of female samples are positive¶

Very heavy bias, since the data is taken when the person is hospitalized¶

sns.set_theme()

def add_title(x, hue, ax=None, title=None):
    if title:
        if ax:
            ax.set_title(title)
        else:
            plt.title(title)
    else:
        if ax:
            ax.set_title(rf"Distribution of {x} $\backsim$ {hue}")
        else:
            plt.title(rf"Distribution of {x} $\backsim$ {hue}")

            
def plot_hist(data, x, hue=None, stat="count", ax=None, xlabel=None, title=None):
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=x, hue=hue, stat=stat, multiple="stack", ax=ax)
    if ax:
        ax.set_xlabel([xlabel, x][xlabel is None])
        ax.set_ylabel(["occurences", "frequency"][stat != "count"])
        add_title(x, hue, ax, title)
    else:
        plt.xlabel([xlabel, x][xlabel is None])
        plt.ylabel(["occurences", "frequency"][stat != "count"])
        add_title(x, hue, ax, title)
        plt.show();

import shutil

# Terminal size. Used later to delimit and separate the different plots
terminal_width, terminal_height = shutil.get_terminal_size((80, 20))


# For every column, we are going to visualize it per sex, and have the target and age as a hue
# to see how everything plays together.
for col in cols:
    
    # TARGET
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.figure.set_figwidth(16)
    fig.figure.set_figheight(13)
    fig.suptitle(f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]}")
    plot_hist(data=df[df["sex"] == 0], x=col, hue="target", stat="percent", xlabel=labels_dict[col],
              title=f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]} for female", ax=axes[0])
    
    plot_hist(data=df[df["sex"] == 1], x=col, hue="target", stat="percent", xlabel=labels_dict[col],
              title=f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]} for male", ax=axes[1])
    plt.show();
    
    # AGE
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    fig.figure.set_figwidth(16)
    fig.figure.set_figheight(13)
    fig.suptitle(f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]}")
    plot_hist(data=df[df["sex"] == 0], x=col, hue="binned_age", stat="percent", xlabel=labels_dict[col],
              title=f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]} for female", ax=axes[0])
    
    plot_hist(data=df[df["sex"] == 1], x=col, hue="binned_age", stat="percent", xlabel=labels_dict[col],
              title=f"Distribution of {labels_dict[col]} for male", ax=axes[1])
    plt.show()
    
    # Plot delimiter
    print("-" * terminal_width)

There seems to be a correlation between chest pain and heart disease.¶

Maximum heart rate in male has a correlation with heart disease. Hard to say anything for women.¶

St depression when low seems to be a good indicator. The age also seems to follow and play a role with it (the older you are the more likely you are to have a low st depression)¶

Correlation for slope when it is high, otherwise not a lot¶

0 vessels colored by fluoroscopy seems to be a strong indicator as well.¶

The % of sick men seem to be quite high. There seems to be a bias from hospitalization. Young hospitalization means there probably is something very wrong, unlike for elders.¶

This effect, while not as severe in women samples, is still present there as well.¶

In [19]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

features = df[[x for x in list(df.columns) if x not in ["target", "binned_age"]]]
pca = PCA(n_components=3)

pca_reduced_features = pca.fit(features)


# Extracting original feature importance
components_influence_ratios = []

for i in range(3):
    components = list(map(lambda x: abs(x), pca_reduced_features.components_[i]))
    
    total = sum(components)
    
    ratios = list(map(lambda x: (x / total) * pca_reduced_features.explained_variance_ratio_[i], components))
    components_influence_ratios.append(ratios)
    
components_influence_ratios = np.array(components_influence_ratios)

# We will handle class imbalance by giving a weight instead of resampling
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

features_list = [x for x in list(df.columns) if x not in ["target", "binned_age"]]
X = df[features_list].values
y = df["target"].values

# Data splitting
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.33, random_state=42)
In [169]:
true_count = len(y_train[y_train == 1])
neg_count = len(y_train[y_train == 0])

true_weight = true_count / (true_count + neg_count)
neg_weight = neg_count / (true_count + neg_count)

weight_dict = {0: neg_weight, 1: true_weight}
weight_array = np.array([1]*y_train.shape[0], dtype="float")  # dtype is very important, otherwise it gets rounded to 0!
for idx, val in enumerate(y_train):
    if val == 1:
        weight_array[idx] = true_weight
    else:
        weight_array[idx] = neg_weight
In [176]:
# Model training and metrics
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

def train_and_test_model(model, model_name, weight_array=None, pca_X_train=None, pca_X_test=None):
    
    X_training = [pca_X_train, X_train][pca_X_train is None]
    X_testing = [pca_X_test, X_test][pca_X_test is None]
    
    if weight_array is not None:
        model.fit(X_training, y_train, sample_weight=weight_array)    
    else:
        model.fit(X_training, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_testing)
    conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(conf_mat, annot=True, fmt="d")
    plt.xlabel("True label")
    plt.ylabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title(f"{model_name} - Classification confusion matrix")
    plt.show()
    
    # Accuracy
    # We only focus on accuracy since both false pos and false neg are important to us to understand the data.
    print(f"Accuracy: {(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred) * 100):.2f} %")
    
    # Feature importance. We cannot access it for SVMs sadly.
    feature_importance_dict = {}
    for label, importance in zip(features_list, model.feature_importances_):
        feature_importance_dict[label] = round(importance * 100) / 100
    print(f"Feature importance: {feature_importance_dict}")

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier,  GradientBoostingClassifier

model = RandomForestClassifier(class_weight=weight_dict)
train_and_test_model(model, "Random Forest")

model = GradientBoostingClassifier()
train_and_test_model(model, "XgBoost", weight_array)

The fact that we get different sets of features isn't a problem, because features are correlated between each others. This means that while we didn't get cholesterole as a high priority feature from the models, due to the correlation it has with other features, we are able to retrieve the information incoded in the cholesterole column¶

Conclusion¶

It is hard to draw any clear cut conclusion from this small biased dataset. However some of the most important indicators to heart disease seem to be the following:¶

{chest pain, nb of major vessels colored by fluoroscopy, heart rate, ST depression due to exercizing[to a lower extent]}¶

The sex of the person doesn't seem to have an impact on the result, and the age seems to have a secondary if not a tertiary impact. Age might however be an indirect cause (for example (imaginary case) old people would have more chest pain)¶

sadly an L1 penalty would have been really useful here to force a better set selection from random forest, but only an L2 one is implemented which doesn't lead to a sparse matrix.¶

On top of these explanations, we have trained some models which could be helpful to predict the urgency of care for a patient at hospitalization time. With hyperparameter tuning we may be able to reach the 85% accuracy rate, but it is unsure if it would make sense since - according to FAMD - the data only explains ~82% of variance.¶

However, if it were to be used, it should be retrained to have recall in mind, in order to give false negatives more importance than false positives.¶
